<tr><td>-</td><td class='diff-deletedline'>== <span class="diffchange">What is this all about? Why a tutorial about filetypes? </span>==</td><td>+</td><td class='diff-addedline'>==<span class="diffchange">Foreword</span>==</td></tr>
<tr><td colspan="2">&nbsp;</td><td>+</td><td class='diff-addedline'><span class="diffchange">This page serves as an introduction to the various filetypes relevant to [[Doom 3 engine]] modding, and is intended for absolute beginners. If you have doubts please post in ths article's [[Talk:Beginner's_Tutorial_(Part_1)_Filetypes|Talk page]].</span></td></tr>
<tr><td> </td><td class='diff-context'></td><td> </td><td class='diff-context'></td></tr>
<tr><td>-</td><td class='diff-deletedline'><span class="diffchange">Since </span>there <span class="diffchange">seems to be </span>a <span class="diffchange">lot </span>of <span class="diffchange">absolute newbies </span>to the <span class="diffchange">Doom 3 modding community</span>, <span class="diffchange">some questions are cropping up again </span>and <span class="diffchange">again</span>. <span class="diffchange">I have seen some info posted about this beginners stuff</span>, <span class="diffchange">but </span>this <span class="diffchange">were posted also by other beginners and therfefore </span>there <span class="diffchange">is </span>a <span class="diffchange">lot </span>of <span class="diffchange">wrong or missleading information floating around</span>. <span class="diffchange">Therefore I decided </span>to <span class="diffchange">clear thing up and hopefully help beginners </span>to <span class="diffchange">get a better understanding of what modding means</span>, <span class="diffchange">especially with regards to coding within the SDK</span>.</td><td>+</td><td class='diff-addedline'><span class="diffchange">==Introduction==</span></td></tr>
<tr><td colspan="2">&nbsp;</td><td>+</td><td class='diff-addedline'><span class="diffchange">On computers </span>there <span class="diffchange">are many different filetypes where each of them serves </span>a <span class="diffchange">specific purpose. Files are just a collection </span>of <span class="diffchange">data somewhere on the hard drive or RAM, and </span>to the <span class="diffchange">computer it doesn't matter what a file exactly contains</span>, <span class="diffchange">because this is only relevant to an application that tries to load the data </span>and <span class="diffchange">work with it</span>. <span class="diffchange">Nevertheless</span>, <span class="diffchange">to make it easier for humans to work with </span>this <span class="diffchange">files, </span>there <span class="diffchange">are some established format conventions. The data in </span>a <span class="diffchange">file can be split into binary and non-binary data. Binary data means that a single byte may contain a character which is in the range </span>of <span class="diffchange">0-255 while non-binary data is limited to a specific range</span>. <span class="diffchange">In order </span>to <span class="diffchange">have human readable text </span>to <span class="diffchange">be recognized</span>, <span class="diffchange">some standardizations were created. The one rather common and relevant for modders is ASCII</span>.</td></tr>
<tr><td> </td><td class='diff-context'></td><td> </td><td class='diff-context'></td></tr>
<tr><td>-</td><td class='diff-deletedline'><span class="diffchange">The purpose </span>of <span class="diffchange">this tutorial is to explain </span>the <span class="diffchange">various filetypes relevant to Doom 3 modding</span>, <span class="diffchange">and is intended </span>for <span class="diffchange">absolute beginners</span>. <span class="diffchange">If you </span>are <span class="diffchange">such a beginner and you </span>don't <span class="diffchange">understand what it means then post </span>a <span class="diffchange">question </span>in the <span class="diffchange">Doom 3 forum for coding and I try </span>to <span class="diffchange">add a better explanation here</span>. <span class="diffchange">Since I'm a professional programmer </span>for <span class="diffchange">more than 20 years now</span>, and <span class="diffchange">by no means I'm a teacher kind of guy, my tutorial </span>may <span class="diffchange">be too advanced without me realizing because </span>this <span class="diffchange">stuff is second nature to me by now</span>. <span class="diffchange">Therfore if something is not explained well it may be because I didn't realize that it should be better explained</span>.</td><td>+</td><td class='diff-addedline'><span class="diffchange">ASCII data contains a subset </span>of the <span class="diffchange">binary characters</span>, <span class="diffchange">which can be printed (</span>for <span class="diffchange">exmaple on a printer), or control some aspect of the printing or display (like FormFeed, LineFeed, etc</span>.<span class="diffchange">). The control characters </span>are <span class="diffchange">also printable, but </span>don't <span class="diffchange">neccessarily translate to </span>a <span class="diffchange">readable character, and perform some function instead. For example, the FormFeed character should, when inserted </span>in <span class="diffchange">a text, force </span>the <span class="diffchange">printer </span>to <span class="diffchange">go the the next page before continuing printing</span>.</td></tr>
