<tr><td>-</td><td class='diff-deletedline'><span class="diffchange">Doom 3 uses a mixture of binary files and ASCII files. Virtuall all of the files that contain game asset data are ASCII files. This is rather advantagous for modders because they can easily change them without an extra application. A variety of files are binary though, which is either out of neccessity or because it offers other advantages. Most notibly the game executable Doom3.exe is a binary file because this can not be something else. Also the gamex86.dll is a binary file, because it is, similar to the EXE file, a binary file by nature. Other files that are binary are the PK4 files which are just renamed ZIP files, OGG files which contain sounds, LWO files which are models created with the Lightwave 3D suite, and MB files which are Maya 3D models and all the image formats for the textures like TGA, JPG and so on. This list is not neccessarily exhaustive though.</span></td><td>+</td><td class='diff-addedline'><span class="diffchange">[[Category:Modding]][[Category:File system]]</span></td></tr>
<tr><td>-</td><td class='diff-deletedline'><span class="diffchange">Most other files are ASCII. Most notibly, the DEF files which contain all kind of game definitions for weapons, models, etc., MTR files which contain material definitions, MAP files which contain the map layout that you can create with the editor when creating a new map, and so on. This list is also not exhaustive, and you can find out about these files when browsing either your D3 directory or look into the PK4 files.</span></td><td>+</td><td class='diff-addedline'></td></tr>

